revision.text:
'''Shirakawa Kuni no Miyatsuko''' (白河国造) was a {{ill|Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|国造|12=draft|12=draft}} of the Shirakawa region, an area corresponding to {{ill|Shirakawa District, Mutsu Province|ja|西白河郡|1=Nishishirakawa District, Fukushima|lt=Shirakawa District|12=draft|12=draft}}, within {{ill|Mutsu Province|ja|Mutsu Province|12=draft|12=draft}}. This area is now part of {{ill|Shirakawa, Fukushima|ja|白河市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nishishirakawa District, Fukushima|ja|西白河郡|1=Nishishirakawa District, Fukushima|lt=Nishishirakawa District|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Higashishirakawa District, Fukushima|ja|東白川郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Ishikawa District, Fukushima|ja|石川郡|12=draft|12=draft}} in modern {{ill|Fukushima Prefecture|ja|福島県|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Overview ==
=== Ancestors === According to the {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, in the 5th year of {{ill|Emperor Seimu|ja|成務天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}'s reign, '''Shioinokoji no Atae''' (鹽伊乃己自直), the 11th-generation descendant of {{ill|Amenoyutsuhiko-no-Mikoto|ja|天由都彦命|12=draft|12=draft}}, was appointed as the Shirakawa Kuni no Miyatsuko.
=== Clan === * The clan was related to the {{ill|Tamanoya clan|ja|玉祖氏|12=draft|12=draft}} and shared kinship with other Kuni no Miyatsuko clans along the {{ill|Tōsandō|ja|東山道|12=draft|12=draft}}, such as {{ill|Shinobu Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|信夫国造|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Someha Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|染羽国造|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Iku Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|伊久国造|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Shita Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|思太国造|12=draft|12=draft}}. * Descendants include the Inoue family. In the 5th year of Keichō (1600), land surveys in the Ino area (now part of Tanagura Town) identified influential local leaders with the surname Inoue, including Inoue Shinano no Kami, Inoue Izumi no Kami, and Inoue Bingo, listed in the survey documents.
=== Historic Sites === * In {{ill|Tanagura, Fukushima|ja|棚倉町|12=draft|12=draft}}, a statue of Jizō (地蔵), called the Ino Jizō-son, enshrines Shioinokoji no Atae. This Jizō statue replaced earlier shrines and torii, reflecting a shift from kami worship to Buddhist syncretism over time, preserving Shioinokoji no Atae’s legacy. * The "Baba Kofun," believed to be Shioinokoji no Atae's tomb, is located behind the Komaru-yama area of [[Tsutsukowake Shrine]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=棚倉町大字沿革誌 |publisher=歴史春秋社 |year=1980 |author=棚倉町教育委員会 |page=4}}</ref>
=== Place Names === According to Tanagura Town’s official website, Shioinokoji no Atae personally tilled the land, transforming it into fertile farmland. Out of gratitude, the locals referred to the area as "Ino" (伊乃), which later evolved into "Irino" (入野). Historical records confirm that names like Inogō, Inoue, and Inoshimo persisted until the early Meiji period, highlighting the area’s deep connection to Shioinokoji no Atae. The modern name of Tanagura derives from the former {{ill|Tanagura Domain|ja|棚倉藩|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Headquarters ==
=== Domain === The Shirakawa Kuni no Miyatsuko governed the region known as Shirakawa Province, later part of Mutsu Province’s Shirakawa District, now encompassing Shirakawa City, Nishishirakawa District, Higashishirakawa District, and Ishikawa District.
During the Ritsuryō system, the area briefly became part of {{ill|Iwasu Province|ja|石背国|12=draft|12=draft}} from the 2nd year of Yōrō (718) to the 6th year of Yōrō (722) or the 1st year of Jinki (724). This region marked the northern boundary of Yamato influence, with Shirakawa Barrier serving as a defensive outpost against the {{ill|Emishi|ja|蝦夷|12=draft|12=draft}}. After the construction of {{ill|Tagajō|ja|多賀城|12=draft|12=draft}}, Shirakawa became a base for the {{ill|Shirakawa Corps|ja|白河団|12=draft|12=draft}}, which guarded the barrier.
== Local Deities ==
* {{ill|Shirakawa Shrine|ja|白河神社|12=draft|12=draft}}: According to its tradition, Shioinokoji no Atae was enshrined there in the 5th year of Emperor Seimu’s reign. The shrine is located at 120 Sekinomori, Hatashuku, Shirakawa City, where Shirakawa Barrier was historically situated. * {{ill|Shirakawa Funada-Honnuma Site Group|ja|白河舟田・本沼遺跡群|12=draft|12=draft}}: Among this group, the {{ill|Shimosōzuka Kofun|ja|下総塚古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}, dated to the late 6th century, is hypothesized to be the tomb of the Shirakawa Kuni no Miyatsuko.
== Notes == {{notelist}}
== References == {{Reflist}}
== Related Articles == * {{ill|List of Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|国造の一覧|12=draft|12=draft}} ** ({{ill|Iwasu Province|ja|石背国|12=draft|12=draft}}: {{ill|Nakadōri|ja|中通り|12=draft|12=draft}}) ** '''Shirakawa Barrier''': Shirakawa (Shirakawa District) - {{ill|Iwasu Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|石背国造|12=draft|12=draft}} (Iwase District) - {{ill|Ashaku Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|阿尺国造|12=draft|12=draft}} (Asaka District) - {{ill|Shinobu Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|信夫国造|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shinobu District) ** ({{ill|Ishikami Province|ja|石城国|12=draft|12=draft}}: {{ill|Hamadōri|ja|浜通り|12=draft|12=draft}}) ** '''Kikuta Barrier''' ({{ill|Nakoso Barrier|ja|勿来関|12=draft|12=draft}}): {{ill|Michioku Kikuta Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|道奥菊多国造|12=draft|12=draft}} (Kikuta District) - {{ill|Ishikami Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|石城国造|12=draft|12=draft}} (Ishikami District) - {{ill|Someha Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|染羽国造|12=draft|12=draft}} (Sometabe District) - {{ill|Ukita Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|浮田国造|12=draft|12=draft}} (Uda District) - {{ill|Iku Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|伊久国造|12=draft|12=draft}} (Igu District) - {{ill|Shi Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|思国造|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shida District) - * Listed south to north. No Kuni no Miyatsuko is associated with the namesake districts of Aizu (Iwasu Province) or Namekata (Ishikami Province).
* {{ill|Shirakawa Yūki Clan|ja|白河結城氏|12=draft|12=draft}}
